@AlexEMG, Thanks for bringing this to my attention!

@eleonoreduroyon, I have a couple of suggestions. First, you could try decreasing the process_ratio variable in deeplabcut/pose_estimation_tensorflow/dataset/pose_dataset_tensorpack.py. The default is set to 6, which is relatively high, so you could begin by training your network with a process ratio of 1 or 2. 

If you continue getting the same error after decreasing the process ratio, here’s something else you can try. There is a warning at the top of your second image that mentions starting a process with ‘fork’ may consume extra memory, and suggests using ‘forkserver/spawn’ instead. It points you to this link to find out more: https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html#contexts-and-start-methods. You can use this library to change the start process to ‘forkserver/spawn’. Alternatively, you could navigate to the directory where you have Tensorpack installed, then go to /tensorpack/utils/concurrency.py and manually change the start process from ‘fork’ to ‘forkserver/spawn’. 

Hopefully this helps, let me know if you are still running into problems after trying these.

